						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">adam_smasher wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">But then he also says:<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"> For one example, Ys 3 mirrors RAM to $70-7f:0000-ffff, but Fire Emblem Thracia 776 maps RAM to $70-7f:0000-7fff, and ROM to $70-7f:8000-ffff.</div><br />Or maybe he's talking about on-cart SRAM?</div><br />Yes, the same sort of RAM that's traditionally mapped to $6000-$7FFF on an NES. As I understand it, mode 21 games map this to $006000-$007FFF, $016000-017FFF, ..., $3F6000-$3F7FFF.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Rather, I would think that the SNES' wiring, before the cartridge even comes into play, should forward read/writes to the cart slot or to RAM based on the particular address requested.</div><br />I think that's what the <a href="http://www.caitsith2.net/snes/flashcart/cart-chip-pinouts.html" class="postlink">/CART signal between A23 and D4</a> is for: an enable for the PRG ROM.</div>

